  "prompt": "Why is diesel lighter than water when the molecular weight of diesel is more?",
  "response": "Diesel is lighter than water due to its composition and density, not solely based on molecular weight. Here are the key reasons:\n\n1. Density differences:\n- Diesel density: ~0.82-0.85 g/cm\u00b3\n- Water density: 1 g/cm\u00b3\n\n2. Composition:\n- Diesel is composed of hydrocarbon molecules (carbon and hydrogen)\n- Hydrocarbons are less dense than water molecules\n- Contains long-chain alkanes and aromatic compounds\n\n3. Molecular structure:\n- Diesel molecules have lower intermolecular forces\n- Less compact molecular arrangement\n- More space between molecules compared to water\n\n4. Molecular weight vs. density:\n- Higher molecular weight doesn't necessarily mean higher density\n- Density depends on molecular arrangement and composition\n\n5. Specific gravity:\n- Diesel's specific gravity is less than 1\n- Means it will float on water\n- Allows easy separation in water-fuel mixtures\n\nThese factors explain why diesel, despite having higher molecular weight, remains lighter and floats on water. Molecular weight is just one aspect of a substance's physical properties, with density and molecular structure also playing crucial roles in determining buoyancy.",
